#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:5
msgid ""
"标题: Gmail’s privacy problem and why it matters\n"
"作者: Ben Wolford\n"
"日期: Thu, 05 Jul 2018 09:21:05 +0000\n"
"链接: https://protonmail.com/blog/google-privacy-problem/"
msgstr ""
"标题: Gmail 的隐私问题以及为什么它很严重\n"
"作者: Ben Wolford\n"
"日期: 7月05日 2018 09:21:05 +0000\n"
"链接: https://protonmail.com/blog/google-privacy-problem/"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:9
msgid ""
"Gmail faced a storm of criticism this week over its practice of sharing "
"users’ \n"
"emails with third-party developers. But Gmail’s failures run much deeper "
"than \n"
"that: The entire business model is incompatible with a free society."
msgstr ""
"Gmail 本周遇到了一场舆论批评风暴，关于它向第三方开发者共享用户邮件的做法。"
"但要知道其实 Gmail 的失败还远远不止这些：其整个商业模式都与一个自由社会不兼容。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:15
msgid ""
"The Wall Street Journal recently published an article highlighting privacy \n"
"concerns related to Gmail’s use of third-party apps[1]. When users install \n"
"tools known as “add-ons” in their Gmail accounts, they are often giving "
"outside\n"
"companies full access to their mailbox. In at least one instance, the WSJ \n"
"reported, “engineers personally read through thousands of emails“."
msgstr ""
"《华尔街日报》最近报道了这件事[1]。当用户在他们的 Gmail 账号里安装一种叫作“插件”"
"的工具时，通常他们也让外面的公司全面访问自己的邮箱了。《华报》说，至少有一例，"
"外面的工程师能够读到上千封电子邮件。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:22
msgid ""
"In the public debate that followed, many people focused on Google’s poor \n"
"oversight of these third-party developers and the inadequacy of their "
"privacy \n"
"policies. While these are important concerns, they distract from the \n"
"fundamental problem with Google, which is that the company’s entire purpose "
"is \n"
"to spy on you and sell your private information to organizations that want "
"to \n"
"influence you."
msgstr ""
"在接下来的舆论辩论中，许多人将焦点放在 Google 糟糕的对第三方开发者的审核，以及"
"他们不完善的隐私政策。虽然这些都是很重要的关注点，但大家都被一个更本质的问题给带跑了："
"Google 这个公司的整体目标就是要监控你们，并且把你们的个人信息卖给那些想影响你的组织。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:24
msgid "The real purpose of Gmail"
msgstr "Gmail 的真实目的"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:28
msgid ""
"Google’s business model is primarily based on online advertising. The "
"company \n"
"earned over $95 billion last year selling the personal information[2] of its "
"\n"
"users to advertisers."
msgstr ""
"Google 的商业模式首先是基于在线广告。公司去年通过售卖其用户的个人信息给广告公司的收入达到 950亿美元。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:34
msgid ""
"For an advertiser, your emails are a gold mine because we often think of "
"email \n"
"as a private communication channel. When your bank contacts you or you "
"address \n"
"an email to your loved one, these seem like two-party conversations. In \n"
"reality, Google treats your Gmail mailbox as company property, scanning them "
"\n"
"with powerful software to better understand you."
msgstr ""
"对广告商来说，你的邮箱就是个金矿，因为我们通常认为电邮是个私人通讯工具。"
"你的银行联系你，或你给你的爱人写电邮，这些都看上去只是双方的对话。实际上，"
"Google 把你的 Gmail 邮箱当作公司的财产，并且用强大的软件扫描你的邮件以更好地了解你。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:39
msgid ""
"Founded in 2004, the service now has 1.4 billion users creating a perfect \n"
"record of their thoughts, behaviors, and interactions. As Google CEO Eric \n"
"Schmidt said in 2010, “We know where you are. We know where you’ve been.We "
"can \n"
"more or less know what you’re thinking about.[3]”"
msgstr ""
"Gmail 服务始于2004年，现在已经有 14 亿用户，他们为自己的想法、行为和互动做了完美的记录。"
"正如 Google CEO Eric Schmidt 在2010年所说：“我们知道你在哪儿，你去过哪儿。我们多少知道你在想什么。[3]”"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:44
msgid ""
"After years of lawsuits and waves of criticism, Gmail finally announced last "
"\n"
"year it would stop scanning users[4]’ inboxes for advertising purposes. What "
"\n"
"they did not mention, however, was that they would continue allow other \n"
"companies to do just that."
msgstr ""
"经过多年的诉讼和批判浪潮， Gmail 最终在去年声明它不再扫描用户[4]的收件箱用于广告目的。然而，他们并没有提到，"
"他们会让其他公司来做这事。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:46
msgid "Third-party data mining in Gmail"
msgstr "Gmail里的第三方数据挖掘"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:52
msgid ""
"Since 2014, Gmail has given third-party developers access to the platform’s "
"\n"
"API, which allows them to build software that can be used within the "
"platform. \n"
"These add-ons are usually productivity tools, such as task managers or "
"document\n"
"signing apps. When users install them, they grant these apps permission to "
"read\n"
"their emails."
msgstr ""
"从2014年开始，Gmail 给予第三方开发者进入平台的API（应用数据接口）的权限，也就是说允许他们能开发在平台内使用的"
"软件。这些附加的软件（简称插件——译者注）通常是一些生产力工具，比如任务管理器或文档签名工具。当用户安装了这些"
"工具，这些工具也就得到了权限来读他们的邮件。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:58
msgid ""
"What is not overtly stated, however, is that the add-ons may actually be a \n"
"front for profitable marketing activities. Buried in their privacy policies "
"are\n"
"vague disclaimers that allow the companies to harvest and share your data "
"with \n"
"their advertising partners. Gmail allows this to happen because third-party "
"\n"
"apps make their platform more valuable."
msgstr ""
"那还没有说在明面的是，这些插件可能就是做有利可图的活动的前端。他们的隐私政策里暗含着模糊的免责声明，允许那些"
"企业收获并分享你的数据给他们的广告合作伙伴。 Gmail 允许这么做就因为第三方应用可以让它的平台更有价值。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:65
msgid ""
"By scanning your emails, companies can learn information about your email \n"
"habits, the things you buy, how much you spend, and who you are. Typically "
"this\n"
"information is anonymized but not always. According to the Wall Street "
"Journal,\n"
"the add-on developers sometimes shared redacted screenshots of entire "
"emails. \n"
"In one instance, two engineers read through 8,000 personal emails in order "
"to \n"
"calibrate their algorithms. The users were never informed about this."
msgstr ""
"通过扫描你的邮箱，企业可以研究你的邮件习惯、你买的东西、你花了多少钱、你是什么人。虽然一般的这些信息都"
"经过匿名化处理，但也并不总是。依据《华报》的叙述，插件的开发者有时还分享整个邮件的截图。"
"其中一个例子就是，两个工程师读了8000封个人邮件，以便校准他们的算法。用户是从没有被告知这个情况的。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:72
msgid ""
"These activities are extremely similar to those that led to the recent \n"
"Facebook-Cambridge Analytica scandal[5]. When the abusive practices of \n"
"Facebook’s third-party app developers came to light, the fallout included a "
"\n"
"#DeleteFacebook hashtag and a congressional inquiry into Facebook’s privacy "
"\n"
"practices. Though Google has so far avoided intense controversy, its \n"
"surveillance operations are far greater than Facebook’s."
msgstr ""
"这些活动都跟最近的脸书-剑桥分析丑闻像极了[5]。当脸书的第三方开发者的滥用行为被曝光后，等来的是 #DeleteFacebook"
"（删除脸书账号——译者注）运动，和国会对脸书公司的隐私相关行为的询问。虽然 Google 直到现在还能避开争议的风头，其实它的监控动作比脸书更甚。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:74
msgid "Privacy is necessary for democracy"
msgstr "隐私是民主的必需品"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:83
msgid ""
"This is not just about strangers having access to your love letters, "
"intimate \n"
"photos and online purchases. It’s also about the kind of society we want to "
"\n"
"live in. Gmail is designed for mass surveillance, and such a powerful tool \n"
"could be easily misused. The intelligence software Google is developing "
"could \n"
"someday be turned against us in ways we cannot predict. The Facebook scandal "
"\n"
"has already given us a glimpse of this power, which can even be used by \n"
"malicious actors to undermine democracy. Imagine if Cambridge Analytica had "
"\n"
"access to your inbox."
msgstr ""
"这可不只是说陌生人看到了你的情信、私密照片和网上购物历史，而是说我们想要生活在一个怎样的社会里。"
"Gmail 就是用来大规模监控的，而且这个强大的工具可以轻易地被滥用。Google开发的这些智能工具哪天就突然把矛头指向"
"我们，用一种我们无法预测的方式。脸书丑闻已经让我们一瞥了这威力，它甚至能被恶势力用来破坏民主制度。"
"想象一下如果剑桥分析公司已经进过了你的收件箱吧。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:90
msgid ""
"Human rights defenders saw the potential for harm from the very beginning of "
"\n"
"Gmail. Five days after its launch, a group of privacy advocates wrote a "
"letter \n"
"to Google expressing their concerns. They said Gmail’s plan to scan emails "
"for \n"
"marketing purposes “violates the implicit trust of an email service "
"provider.” \n"
"Gmail has violated that trust again and again, and it will continue to do so "
"\n"
"because invading people’s privacy is essential to its business model."
msgstr ""
"人权捍卫者们在 Gmail 刚出的时候就意识到了这个潜在的危害。它发布五天后，一组隐私倡导者给Google写了封信表达了他们"
"的关切。他们说 Gmail对邮件进行市场营销为目的的扫描的计划是“对一个邮件服务者的信任的破坏”。Google 一再破坏了"
"这信任，它还会继续这样做，因为侵入他人隐私是他基本的商业模式。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:92
msgid "How to protect your privacy in the age of Google"
msgstr ""
"在谷歌帝国时代怎样保护你的隐私"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:102
msgid ""
"Fortunately, the ad-based business model is not the only viable way to \n"
"commercialize online services. At ProtonMail, we implement end-to-end \n"
"encryption, which means users have the only keys to their data. Your inbox "
"is \n"
"safe from corporate surveillance and offers increased security in the event "
"of \n"
"a data breach. Encryption also makes targeted advertising impossible. So "
"while \n"
"we offer free accounts, we are supported almost entirely by paid users. This "
"\n"
"means our interests are aligned with those of our users, most of whom "
"believe \n"
"paying money is preferable to paying with their data, given the privacy and "
"\n"
"security risks."
msgstr ""
"幸运的是，世上并不只有基于广告的商业模式才算有效的商业在线服务。在 Protonmail，我们采用端对端加密技术，意味着"
"只有用户才有进入他们数据的钥匙。你的收件箱对于大企业的监控是安全的，且在数据泄漏发生时更安全。加密同样能让"
"定向广告变得不可能。所以当我们提供免费账号时，我们几乎只由付费用户来支撑我们的业务。这说明了我们的志趣和我们的"
"用户的志趣——那些相信付费是对他们的数据、隐私和安全风险的保障的人——是一致的。"

#: Gmails_privacy_problem_and_why_it_matters.txt:107
msgid ""
"When you pay for the services you use, you can be sure you are the customer "
"and\n"
"not the product being sold to advertisers. If you’re tired of your personal "
"\n"
"information being sold, processed, and profiled, then consider switching to "
"a \n"
"service that puts privacy first."
msgstr ""
"当你对你使用的服务付费，你很确定你就是个消费者而非被当作产品卖给广告商。如果你厌倦了自己的个人信息被卖、被"
"分析和被建档，那么可以考虑换到一个隐私优先的服务吧。"

